        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>[CII] is expected to be the brightest FIR cooling line, and we assume it carries 0.5% of the total FIR luminosity (but it could be as high as 1% as this is a normal galaxy with an intrinsic L_IR &lt; 10^11 L_o). We base our estimate of the total FIR luminosity on the observed Spitzer MIPS 24 um flux (400 mJy - observed), and assume the spectral energy distribution of the galaxy can be modeled by a Chary &amp; Elbaz (2001) SED. This yields an integrated (apparent) luminosity of L_IR = 3 x 10^12 L_o. Assuming a line width of 300 km/s, implies a [CII] flux of line of ~ 500 mJy (spatially integrated). This emission is expected to be distributed over the eastern RCS0327 arc component, as evidenced by the ~ 10" extent of the 24  um emission, consistent with the brightest optical emission in the HST image. Therefore, given that the beam will be ~ 0.16" at 704 GHz in configuration 4 we assume the [CII] emission is uniformly distributed over 60 beams (a conservative estimate – more likely the emission will be concentrated in more compact clumps, in which case we will detect these with high significance). Therefore we require a sensitivity to detect a peak line flux of 8 mJy beam^-1 at 5-sigma. The arc is stretched with extreme aspect ratio and its width is less than the maximum resolvable angular scale so we do not expect to resolve out any diffuse emission. For time estimation we chose 75 km/s channels, but note that if the line is brighter than we estimate (for example, if the I(CII)/I(FIR) ratio is closer to 0.01) or clumpy (as it surely is) we can bin at finer velocity resolution (the coarsest spectral resolution available in band-9 is ~ 14 km/s). The line-integrated emission will be detected at much higher significance, and will allow us to generate a high-quality map of the resolved [CII]. The continuum will come for free at high S/N (see below).

Integration Time Required: We base our time estimate on the requirement to achieve a sensitivity of 1.5 mJy beam^-1  r.m.s. at 704 GHz in typical (‘Calculator chooses’) weather. As described above, this is a conservative estimate of the sensitivity required to detect the resolved [CII], assuming the integrated 500 mJy is evenly distributed over 60 beams and a minimum significance of 5-sigma. The OT indicates a time of 1.83h on source, or 4.88h including all overheads. Simultaneously we will be measuring continuum over nearly 8 GHz of bandwidth. For the same integration time, this will provide us with a sensitivity of 0.2 mJy r.m.s., Using the 24 um again as a guide we expect the observed 450 um flux to be ~ 2 Jy/beam and thus the continuum detection will be highly significant. 

Angular Resolution: One of the advantages of working with the [CII] line is that it falls in Band-9 where spatial resolution is optimized. We select configuration 4 which provides 0.16" resolution, optimizing the comparison with the IR IFU (0.15") and the HST (0.11") images. This corresponds to an astonishing 20-200 pc in the source plane (the size range corresponds to the range in magnification across the arc, not an uncertainty).
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
